comment: Professor Roberts is the most incredible teacher I have ever learned from. His lectures are captivating, and he cultivates an engaging and interactive learning environment. He made a three hour Monday morning class feel like 45 minutes. I wish I had more space for detail, but his class and teaching truly changed my life. Please take his class.

Professor Roberts, especially in How to Make a Racist, was hands-down the best professor I've had. He knows how to ask the right questions to get you to think deeper about the material and always gives ample and constructive feedback. Professor Roberts is unique because, not only is he an amazing professor, he's an amazing person.

Professor Roberts is very intelligent, and his class has inspired me to become more engaged with the world to make a positive impact. He's considerate and cares about all of his students equally. His approach to the content of class is thoughtful and his talks are well-prepared and intentional. His teaching style makes it easy for anyone to learn.

TOP TIER! I love Professor Roberts so much! This is my second quarter having him and every class with him teaching is a joy! If you ever get the opportunity to take one of his classes, DO IT! I am forever grateful and honored to say that I have been one of your students.

Out of all the classes I've taken at Stanford so far this has been my favorite, and I'd highly recommend anyone to take this class. Professor Roberts creates a welcoming classroom environment that's also conducive to academic/personal exploration. Moreover, he's incredibly insightful and inspiring. Super glad I took this class!

Professor Roberts is truly one of the best instructors I've ever had. He's very down to earth, kind, funny, and not too lax. He did a great job at making our class feel comfortable and respected when sharing. He always comes to class in a positive mood. I look forward to taking courses with him in the future, I learned so much from him.
Steven Roberts
He is an amazing professor and I highly recommend his courses. He doesn't have favorites and his class is very inspirational. My favorite class as a Freshman!

Mr. Roberts is a great professor! He truly cares about us students and our personal development. One of my favorite and most memorable classes I've taken at Stanford. I can't say enough good things - highly recommend!

Professor Roberts is an AMAZING professor and helped me discover myself through this class. He's so caring, helpful, and understanding that I don't even know how to put it into words. Completely changed my outlook on my life and made me a much more understanding and respectful person!

This was easily my favorite class at Stanford! Professor Roberts is AMAZING. He ensures his students feel comfortable and goes the extra mile to get to know you personally. You can tell he genuinely cares about his students. He has truly changed my outlook on life and I am so grateful to have taken this class.

Professor Roberts is absolutely incredible, teaching some mix between meditation, therapy, writing, and I can say that I loved it with all my heart. This is thanks to the care and attention that he allots to us. It's a truly transformative experience. I cant thank him enough for creating something so special for its very first iteration.

Professor Steven Roberts is beyond phenomenal. His dedication to creating a welcoming and caring environment is evident, and he goes far out of his way to make sure that everyone feels included and valued. The course syllabus was revised a lot, but it also was his first conception and realization of this course, and the class was still so valuable.

In my eyes, this course is a model example of a seminar. His curation of activities across the quarter were exceptionally thoughtful, and peer-led class discussions offered real insight into racism in a way that could not be achieved through readings. Rarely ever thought about my grade, just wanted to keep learning and improving myself.

He is simply super chill and cool. The inspiration to make a change in the world in terms of race equality. The reading are sometimes hard to understand but very interesting to discuss in class. 
He creates a very comfy place to express our thoughts freely:)

Professor Roberts is a great guy! I'm a conservative, and I took his class-- How to Make a Racist. And though I don't agree with all the things in class discussions, he is very welcoming of differing opinions, and I appreciate that. I learned a lot in his class. He is very understanding and kind. You should take HTMAR if you get the chance!
Look at those reviews. Clustered at/near the same date. Same/almost the same scores given. Tell me those aren't rigged.

you will not regret taking a class with professor roberts. he is incredibly down to earth and passionate about what he does. Within How to Make a Racist, he does not emphasize grades because he actually wants us to engage and understand the concepts. I signed up for Psych 1 in the winter because of him.

Prof Roberts is amazing!! I genuinely looked forward to going to his class every day. His teaching style is student-friendly and engaging; lectures were always great (& often hilarious), and small group discussions were frequent. The sense of closeness & openness he created in the class is truly unmatched. Take this prof--you'll be glad you did!
Professor Stevens was incredible, his course made me a better student and overall human being. He is talented above measures in terms of teaching and connecting with students.

Without a doubt, Prof. Roberts is the best teacher I've had in my entire life! He is EXTREMELY passionate, enthusiastic, and knowledgeable about the material, and he made every single class an absolute joy. I've never seen a teacher care so deeply about every student in his class. The material is relevant to literally every subject you can imagine!

Professor Roberts is an amazing teacher who really cares about his students & creates a supportive environment for sharing. Each class we discussed different racial concepts while also having fun activities and sharing our own experiences. Overall, it was a privilege to be part of this class and I hope everyone has the chance to take it!

Prof. Roberts is an incredible teacher, thinker, and person. He was extremely energetic, engaging, and passionate EVERY. SINGLE.CLASS! He cares about each one of his students on a personal level and creates a safe space to discuss difficult issues. He made our class into a family and inspired us to become better learners, people, and antiracists.

Professor Roberts genuinely puts so much effort into teaching. His How to Make a Racist intro-sem is something I wish was mandatory for every freshman at Stanford. He'll help you broaden your perspective and truly emphasize the direct paths to anti-racism based on what causes racism in the first place identifying distinct and valuable psychology.
This is a life-changing course and Dr. Roberts is a life-changing man. He makes class very engaging and keeps everyone engaged. He is amazing at teaching not only the material but why it matters.
Amazing class. Amazing professor. Amazing opportunity. Thanks, Prof!

This class was amazing! Psych 21N is by far my favorite class I've taken at Stanford. This class made me self-reflect and has definitely made me grow. The things we learn in this class are truly useful and essential in the real word-- unlike other courses. Plus, Professor Roberts is such a great professor who genuinely cares about his students!

Professor Roberts's psych 21N class is a life-changing experience. Truly the best professor I've ever had, as he helps you grow personally while presenting intellectually challenging questions to you. Taking this class will change your perspective regardless of your major. Both Roberts and this class are a must have.

Steven is literally the best professor I've had in a long time. I took Psych 1 in the fall, and I had to have him again as a teacher, so I signed up for his introsem, which was probably the best decision I could have ever made. He made such a safe and welcoming environment, and he was just as giving to the class as he expected us to be. A true gift

Professor Roberts is, hands down, the most influential teacher I've had at Stanford. He wields the full power of education to create a lasting impact on his students to do good in the world. Through group discussions, readings and assignments, I came out of his class with new perspective, insight and passion.

Jump at every opportunity you have to learn from Prof. Roberts. In addition to being the best professor I've had at Stanford, he is just an incredible human being - genuine, hilarious, and exceptionally kind. Even in the Zoom age, every single reading, lecture, discussion, and assignment in his class was engaging, informative, and meaningful.

Dr. Robert's instruction and knowledge changed my life. I've grown a lot from taking PSYCH 21N and I feel like I have the power to initiate positive social change. Dr. Robert's fostered an unparalleled sense of community in class during this virtual year and really made sure each student had the chance to share their experiences. 10/10 recommend!

This is one of the best teachers I've ever had in my entire life. Period. He really cares about his students and what they learn from his class, and it's so inspirational to see. A true gem here at Stanford <3

Professor Roberts is the most understanding, and inspirational professor I have ever had (and I think ever will have). I know some people get really skeptical of super positive reviews in any context, but honestly, this is one of the best human beings I have ever had the pleasure of getting to know.

Professor Roberts is an incredible educator and person, finding creative, engaging, and all-around genius ways to keep our attention on Zoom while also deepening our understanding of course concepts. The course was well-structured: readings were relevant; lectures built upon themselves. Roberts gives constructive, supportive feedback. Very kind.

I've never seen a teacher investing so much time, energy, thought into a group of students as much as Pof. Roberts. Not only does he teach charismatically, he fosters student engagement so that there would be real connection - even over Zoom. Prof. label aside, he is an inspiration and a powerhouse. It was a HUGE privilege to be in his class.

Quite literally the best professor I've ever had. Genuinely cares about his students and really makes the class a safe space where we can be vulnerable and have fun. Great a creating a community during zoom and taught us some life changing material. Only complaint is he can't play basketball :/ Seriously, great professor and great dude!

Steven Roberts is the best professor I have ever had. He is truly second to none. His lectures are interactive and engaging, his jokes are awesome, and he truly cares about his students and what they learn. I took his course called "How to Make a Racist" and I am forever changed. If he is your Professor, consider yourself exceptionally lucky.

I learned so much from Professor Roberts about psychology and the world! He thoroughly explained course concepts and how they could be applied to the real world. I especially appreciated his commitment to making time for all of us who wanted to stay after class and that he encouraged us every step of the way. Best professor I have ever had!

Professor Roberts made this the most inspiring class of the quarter for me. He turned a hard and uncomfortable topic (confronting racism) into something fun (but not light!). The class was super insightful, forced me to reflect on myself, and has done more than anything else I've experienced to motivate me to act. He also fostered some friendships!

Although I'm just a freshman, I know that this class will be the best class I will have taken at Stanford. Professor Roberts is the GOAT. He is super energetic, loves his students, and pushes you to be a better person. Extremely knowledgable! He's alright at basketball too.

Professor Roberts is the absolute best professor I have ever had in my academic career. He truly cares about his students and that they leave his class not only better students, but better people. I enjoyed coming to class every single day and Professor Roberts' positive energy is contagious. Do everything in your power to TAKE THIS CLASS!!!

This class changed my perspective on racism in America. I have never been so impacted by a class in my whole life. Despite being on zoom, I think I grew more in 10 weeks learning from Professor Roberts than I have ever in my life.

comment: Great and energetic lecturer who made attending classes fun and engaging. Definitely recommended. Take PSYCH 1 with him over other faculty, who gave less than stellar guest lectures during the course of his teaching term.

Professor Roberts seriously changed my perspective on the world. I took his class "How to Make a Racist" at Stanford University. This class caused me to think critically about racism in the world and gave me the tools to be anti-racist. He seamlessly weaves relevant academic material and personal experiences together to make a profound curriculum.

Professor Roberts is one of the most incredible humans you'll meet. His lived values of standing up against injustice are inspiring beyond words, and it's nearly impossible to walk away from his class without feeling more empowered to tackle systemic racism and call out the racist thinking within yourself. He is amazing!

The course is life-changing, and Professor Roberts is amazing in his care, passion, and love for students. He makes it a priority to get to know every one individually, and fosters participation and deep topics in discussion.

Professor Roberts was one of my most favorite professors. If you ever have a chance to take any class with him, it would be a crime not to! He is easy to talk to, cares about his students, and isn't afraid to share a few laughs.

One of the best professors at this school. You can tell he cares for his students and is dedicated to decreasing racism. He is inspirational, and his introsem is beautifully crafted. Ive never had a class completely change the way I think. He does an amazing job cultivating a safe space where we can be vulnerable and really learn from others.

This class was so amazing and opened my eyes in so many different ways. Roberts was such an awesome, inspirational and passionate professor that it was impossible not to be completley amazed by the lessons learned in each class.

What makes Professor Roberts so special is his genuine compassion for everyone taking his class. He empathizes with his students, using their own examples as evidence for the structures he's teaching. I would highly recommend anyone take a discussion based class with him.

Professor Roberts is someone so inspiring, genuine, and knowledgeable of what he's teaching that there is almost no way to hate this class! I learned so much about myself and the inner workings of society, and Roberts was so caring throughout the duration of the course. If you fail to learn anything, I am positive you will learn more about yourself

Professor Roberts is genuinely a gem. He is a great teacher who really cares about his students and looks to involve all of them in the class. He truly cares about what he teaches, makes class lively and interesting, and constantly looks for ways to improve and better his classes. If you ever have the opportunity to learn from him, please take it.

Professor Roberts provided a comfortable space to talk about important issues that currently harm our society. He was able to bring a group of diverse students to discuss an intimate topic while simultaneously creating a fun experience. He is also willing to be vulnerable with his students, which made the conversations in class even more open.

Dr. Roberts has created an incredibly unique environment. We learn in both a traditional academic way and a more unique discussion based way that elicits feelings and personal ties to the material. He's an awesome teacher, mentor, and facilitator.
Professor Roberts is an exceptional professor and individual. He knows what to say, how to teach concepts well, and leave you feeling absolutely inspired. Any class with him would be a joy to take.

Professor Roberts is absolutely the best professor that I have ever had in my entire educational career. He is the most kind and empathetic person that I have met possibly on the face of this Earth. He is amazing at maintaining the balance between professionalism and relatability. He brought a bunch of strangers together and made us into friends.

Professor Roberts is the best professor I have ever had. He is so passionate about his work, which inspires everyone in the class to participate and engage with all the topics in class and take them into the real world. His classed changed my life, I sound dramatic, but it really did change my understanding of the world. Take his class!

Professor Roberts is the most caring, insightful, and easy-to-talk to person out there. He truly cares about social issues, community, and instilling ethical values within his students that will carry on over for a lifetime.

Professor Roberts is by far the greatest instructor I have ever had. How to Make a Racist changed my world view and I could not imagine anyone else doing such an amazing job. If you are split between two classes or unsure, take his class! You will not regret it!

10/10 I'd recommend HTMAR to any & all freshmen at Stanford Prof Roberts created an environment in which all of the students were comfortable sharing personal experiences, discuss the difficult topic of race, & genuinely be excited to learn about concepts & connect them to our daily lives. Though the subject matter was heavy, class was still fun :)

Professor Roberts is genuinely the best teacher I have ever had, and Psych 21N was the best course I've ever taken; I can say for certain that my life has been changed for the better by Prof Roberts. When I think of a "Stanford" experience, I think of Professor Roberts and Pysch 21N.

Dr. Steven Roberts' lectures were phenomenal. Not only were they very entertaining (by far the most enjoyable lectures I've had), but they also beautifully connected the material to the real world. He was also incredibly flexible when it came to meeting outside of class, and he stayed after every single lecture to answer questions. Take his class.

A wonderful teacher, definitely the best professor and class Ive had so far at Stanford. Really cares about all his students and wants them to take something significant / meaningful away from his class.

Steven is an exceptional mentor, professor, and individual. The amount of dedication and effort he puts into setting up a inclusive and engaging environment for his students is astounding. Definitely recommend taking a class with him or even just getting to know him :)

Professor Roberts is quite possible the best teacher I could have in my first quarter at Stanford. Going into the class, I was worried I would be overwhelmed by the serious topic of racism. His lectures and the discussions he leads get the whole class engaged and creates an atmosphere in which everyone can share their opinions and learn. Amazing!!!
Genuinely a great guy. Bless up.

This course is a must take! It will change your perspective on race, racism, and yourself. The class is discussion based and participation is mandatory! The more that you put in to discussion, the more you will get out of it. Sections are always interesting and the work load is very manageable. Highly recommend taking a class with this professor!!

Steven Roberts is an AMAZING professor and really dedicates his time into making this class the most informative experience that it can be. This class truly opens your eyes to the intricacies of building racism in America and definitely recommend it to all people. Amazing class and don't miss out on a chance to take from him!

Professor Roberts makes an incredibly important and difficult subject approachable and powerful. Take this class if you care at all about your role in a racial hierarchy no matter your skin tone. These are the most important lessons you can learn in college and beyond.
Great introductory race class from a professor who clearly cares about the subject matter. Definitely recommend.

comment: Steven is an absolutely amazing professor. Every day he pushed me to reconsider what I thought I knew about race and racism, and upon finishing his class, I feel more prepared to take on the world around me. I would recommend him and his class to anyone. Thank you, Steven!!!

Amazing course! I learned so much, and Steven is an incredible professor who genuinely cares about his students learning. comment: Professor Roberts really is invested in creating a supportive and rich classroom environment. He took the time at the beginning of the quarter to meet with each of the students to get to know them and I've never had a professor do that before. He also is very knowledgeable and a asks probing but important questions. Class discussion was great.

TAKE ANY AND EVERY CLASS WITH HIM YOU CAN. But honestly, Prof. Roberts is hands down one of the best teachers I have ever had. Steven is quite invested in the individual experience of each of his students. He holds short 1 on 1 meetings at the beginning of the year and sustains open communication throughout the course. Steven is an absolutely incredible professor. He structured the class with such thought and care, and he really fostered a great learning environment. He made talking about uncomfortable topics comfortable.
Incredible class and professor. You can tell that he genuinely cares about all of his students and what he is teaching. 10/10 recommend any class taught by Professor Roberts.

Professor Steven Roberts is a professor that truly cares about what his students think. comment: Professor Roberts was a phenomenal instructor. Moral Foundations of Capitalism with Prof. McCaskey is a wonderful class. I ended up changing my views about many of the authors we read and learned a lot about both the supporters and detractors of capitalism. Definitely one of the most interesting classes at Stanford. I would recommend this to anyone regardless of political persuasion.

Professor McCaskey has lots of energy and enthusiasm for the class, which made me much more excited about the subject. He is incredibly helpful and always willing to work with students outside of class to make sure they understand the material. He also gave great essay feedback and helped us outside of class to improve our writing.

Phenomenal teacher. I learned more in this class than I have in any other class at Stanford.  Really challenges students to think critically and to thoroughly understand concepts.  Very approachable.  Was determined to schedule time with students outside of class if he felt they weren't fully grasping the concepts.

Moral Foundations of Capitalism with Prof. McCaskey is an excellent class. Prof. McCaskey challenges every student to challenge and formulate her personal economic and political philosophy or at least understand and challenge those of the writers we read. He is readily available to help and is a great asset to his students academic careers.

I took the Moral Foundations of Capitalism with Professor McCaskey, and it was a great class.  Professor McCaskey is all you could ask for and them some: smart, fun, helpful, and caring.  I looked forward to going to his class because it was fun and I learned so much.  He is also a fine writer; your writing will improve if you take his class.

Professor McCaskey is good at helping students think about the course concepts. He did this by relating the readings to each other, providing readings with different moral arguments, and giving us detailed feedback on completed papers and drafts. The class environment made it easy for students who weren't familiar with the material to participate.

Professor McCaskey is everything a college class needs. His course provides a variety of viewpoints on ideas that are important to students and demands nothing but the best thinking from all.  Best professor at Stanford thus far.

Professor McCaskey opened my eyes to an entirely new world of that that I had not previously explored.  He did of incredible job of helping grasp complex philosophical concepts and begin to formulate my owns opinions and judgments on the subject.  He shared a genuine excitement for the material that was infectious and inspiring.

Professor McCaskey is an amazing professor. I took Moral Foundations of Capitalism, and it helped me formulate my own beliefs much more coherently. He handles discussions well, he brings a lot of passion to class, and his explanations are crystal clear. It was the best class I've taken so far, and I recommend that everyone try his classes.

Professor McCaskey is a talented educator. I looked forward everyday to attending his class and sharing the excitement he brings to learning. He did an incredible job of teaching a difficult subject and addressing the variety of student backgrounds and needs in the course. I highly recommend that everyone studies with McCaskey during college.

Professor McCaskey's enthusiasm for course material was contagious. The course was well designed with a clear progression and development of central themes. I took a lot away from the course and highly recommend Dr. McCaskey to other students. He's one of the best professors I've had at Stanford.
Professor McCaskey is everything higher education needs: a teacher who cares about his students, incorporates a wide variety of  viewpoints, and thoughtfully prepares the course.

This class was great.  McCaskey knows his subject, and his enthusiasm is infectious.  Even students who had no prior interest in 19th century philosophy of science seemed engaged and excited.  Overall, a great experience.  Take a class from this guy.

Professor McCaskey is by far and away the best professor at Stanford university. I have never taken such an enjoyable and interesting class. He is an incredible professor!

Prof. McCaskey is amazing.  This class was one of the best classes I've ever taken, and most of that is due to his way of teaching and engaging students in meaningful and insightful discussions.  Awesome!
the class was very enjoyable, largely due to Dr. McCaskey's charisma and an excellent reading list.

this man was enthusiastic and passionate about the course. the course covered 2500 years of the history of science and logic, and he was versed in every topic of discussion. he is as likable as he is intelligent. if you like the history of science and want to read Newton, Galileo, Aristotle, Heisenberg, Copernicus, and others, this is the course!!

Prof. McCaskey is extremely knowledgeable, and his class was really cool and interesting. His standards are high but fair. His real strength in class is leading excellent discussions which are engaging and informative and, most of all, really bring the readings to life.
Excellent teacher. Very excited about the material, very interested in what the students have to say. The best class I have taken here.

AST 1001 Summer term 2024, UMN

He's adorable.
Great professor! Knowledgeable and engaging.

Genuinely a terrific professor!

Prof. Gill is a passionate professor who gives great lectures. He's really kind, and generous one of my favorite professors here!!!

Thank you for being an amazing professor.

Excellent class and instructor. Prof. Gill is able to take advanced concepts in astronomy and physics and explain them to students. Very nice individual and really wants his students to succeed.

comment: BEST PROFESSOR EVER

Professor Starkman is a little intimdating. She's very welcoming in class and encouraging. Then she rips your work to shreds. Literally. Every. Word. But then she shows you how to improve and she makes you want to do better. In the end you do OK, make friends in class, and learn a lot.

Here's the thing  with Professor Starkman. She's super smart and has zero patience for dogma of any kind. Don't just come in and spout off your private theory of ethics. You will just embarrass yourself. The reading is hard . You need to do it before class and be prepared. See her in her office hours, she's not that intimidating in person.

The stuff I learned with Professor Starkman has stayed with me for years, and when you go back to visit she remembers you perfectly like no time has gone by. Ask her for help on job apps and gradmed school, nobody goes the extra mile like she does.
The one professor who's taught  me most in my Stanford career.

comment: The first half of each lecture is typically an explanation of the concepts, and the second half is done on the whiteboard and/or a live demo on screen. Professor Liang writes code faster than anyone I've ever seen!

Lawrence Lessing or should I say best teacher ever? "The Law" is his self-proclaimed nickname. You learn so much in class. He assigns like 200 pages of reading a night, but Law is the most interesting subject ever, so it's fine!

Not the most personable guy, but very smart, and he really teaches you about how the Supremes go about assessing cases (based on his knowledge as a former clerk an a very close observer of the caselaw).

I disagree with the others; I think they should consider the whole package, and walk a mile in his shoes. His contributions to law, policy and society are unparalleled. He cares deeply about his students. He cares deeply about the subjects.  His lack of slickness (ala Grundfest) or pomposity (ala Brest) are attributes, not limitations.

Terrible.  The worst professor I've had in law school.  Brilliant, but arrogant and should not be teaching large classes.  Unhelpful, won't meet with students, and cares only about teaching HIS theory.
Felt like he read the material the night before, and was blessing us with his insights.
rude and obnoxious to students-- even in class. He's entirely self-absorbed.  still, his lectures are interesting even if he's scary.

Classic programmer that was NOT born to teach. Speaks with a very nasal-y mumble while pacing around. Reads off slides crowded with code or trivial points that are probably on the test. No live coding demos, real-world connections, or information actually needed for projects. Rude in his Piazza answers. I've seen better community college professors
He clearly knows his stuff. A little bit mumbling in speech.
he liked to wear crocs before they were cool

Good at answering questions via email and after class, but not in office hour.   Lecture is not interesting but clear enough. He speaks fast. His tone is too flat to make you sleepy.   Final exam questions are interesting.
Could be more enthusiastic, not the best teacher, but not the worst.
No Comments

Professor Sagan is very intelligent, and his passion for non-proliferation is inspiring. However his arrogance pushes students away. 3 other reviewers have mentioned his "arrogance" and "hubris". I sadly cannot agree more. Very intelligent. But little respect for students who are just getting interested in his subject.
Prof. Sagan is knowlegeable but suffers from scholastic hubris. Like many others I am sure that he would like to be the next Kissinger or Condi.

Brilliant lecturer, very clear, well-structured presentations, good insight. He expects analytic rigor from his students. It is unsurprising that some people bear a grudge when they don't get to coast through the class.   The ratings don't really reflect how good an instructor he is.  Better to trust the high enrollment for non-required classes.

Professor Sagan is quite knowledgeable and seriously committed to international security.However,he is like other policy wonk types who belong to the CFR--namely, full of hubris and set in his ideological ways.
No Comments
A serious professor with a low level of tolerance for student error. Kind of arrogant despite his knowledge of the material and certainly not too keen about Bush or the Republicans.
Brilliant man
Crystal clear teacher. Never saw a teacher with such clear teaching in class.

Prof. White is the BEST.  Incredibly smart and can lecture without using any notes.  His speaking style is such that you're always engaged.  I took his class as an EE major and almost switched to math.  He's really friendly in office hours and very personable too if you ever invite him to faculty night.  Prof. White is a real treasure.

Professor White does a good job of clearly explaining mathematical concepts from a technical perspective, taking care to prove each of his theorems as he teaches. Easily one of the most popular professors of introductory math classes. Plus, he wears crazy Hawaiian shirts.
absolutely amazing. Everyone in every other lecture for math 51 this term ended up in professor white's lecture because he is simply that good.
Best teacher I've had in the math department--no surprise he's the only lecturer you're allowed to have if you're in ACE (accelerated calculus for engineers.) Clear, fair, and makes it interesting
Um, no.
Prof Block is brilliant and very clear, but lacks empathy and a moral core.  He seems driven to act in a way that is best described as evil.  Stay out of this man's orbit.

I'm not fond of this rating system; although Block wasn't necessarily "crystal clear" or "extremely helpful," he was still awesome! He was so enthusiastic about the subject and thrilled with teaching it to us! I don't know how he would be with more dry material (we studied Mythbusters and the scientific process), but he was great for this class.
awesome!
a nice guy, expects alot, just make sure you've thought about your question seriously before you go asking for help.
Evil.  Very harsh and demoralizing.
Pretty good. I went to office hours once.
I thought she was helpful and i learned a lot.
i don't know what they are talking about - i liked her,
A lot of work and Elrad is no help.

worst prof ever, and i really mean that. she's not even a professor, just a some plant biologist hired as a lecturer. she is completely inept as a lab manager and universally hated by the students.   oh, and very not hot

Dafna Elrad is the worst teacher I've ever had.  Her grading practices were blatantly unfair (she flunked a number of students on their decently-written lab reports), and she did not maintain the laboratory equipment, even after the supply manager warned her that the experiments wouldn't work if she did not do so.  Don't take a class from her.
love Abrams!! He's very thought provoking and the grading is lenient if you are thoughtful in your papers. He let me do the work and be interested without having to worry about my grade too much.

While the class wasn't particularly hard to do well in, it didn't need to be. Professor Abrams inspires his students to be better at everything they do, including in this class. I thoroughly enjoyed both classes I took with him, and I would highly recommend anything he is teaching, even if it is not in your area of study.
Wonderful teacher, very passionate about what he teaches...go visit and talk with him if you get the chance.

Great professor, engaging class.  He wouldn't just lecture, he'd get conversations and debates started.  The class is pretty easy-- it's easy to get away with not doing the reading, and he practically tells you how to pass the final, but it was a fantastic class.  More than any other class at Stanford, this one taught me a new way to think.
Excellent Professor.  Easy class.  Too much work for 3 units though.  12 Page research paper, group project and a Final.

She teaches oil politics and a research seminar.  I strongly recommend her because of how intelligent, informed, and articulate on a multitude of political issues.  Her instruction was particularly helpful in helping me to state my ideas clearly.  I admire her and I would tell anyone to take her class.
One of the best professors at Stanford. If you don't take a class with her you missed out.
Just an average instructor. Seems good just by comparison with the rest of the bunch
great!
No Comments
good, insightful lectures. awesome class. LOTS of reading. if you study hard and write papers well, you'll get an A.
The most inspirational faculty I encountered in my 4 years at Stanford. Changed the course of my life toward music.
Robert is fabulous, makes choir so much fun!
University Singers is tons of fun.
Robert makes u. singers a lot of fun!
Robert is so much fun!
No Comments
Excellent professor and mentor.
Heather is an amazing professor with such joy and enthusiasm about her subject matter. One of the best prof's I've had in the music dept.
I agree. The article was very illuminating. I can't say it added to my knowledge of music but it certainly improved my sex life! And isn't that what college is for?
I can't comment on her lecturing, but I highly recommend everyone check out her seminal 1995 article published in the Journal of Sex Research.  I know it made my quarter.
Boring. Harsh grader. It's an intro seminar for gosh sakes! (she's nice though)...
Boy, this lady is stupid. I can't believe she's a Stanford professor!
I watched his lectures on youtube. I'm not a stanford student, but looking at what he does in class, he loves to mess around with people, but he's good.
Great professor, presents good lectures and has a great sense of humor!
Amazing professor. Take Intro to ChemE even if you aren't majoring in engineering.

Probably the best professor at Stanford.  After taking his class, I am completely dedicated to the Chemical Engineering major.  His teaching style is exceptionally engaging, his lectures are laced with lots of funny stories.  I can't wait to TA for him this spring.

Best Teacher at stanford!!

(237D) Undoubtedly one of the most knowledgeable professors I ever had the chance to learn from, but Baker's unapproachable and snobbish demeanor made office hours useless when attended. He tends to get annoyed when he thinks that a student isn't understanding something he thinks is obvious, and it made his class frustrating and uncomfortable.
He's insanely smart and famous, but he also has a wicked dry sense of humor, and he really does care about his students.
professor baker is one of the smartest people on the planet

Absolutely well learned and knowledgeable on all aspects of history throughout this century. Incredibly dedicated to the applications of historic actions in todays globe including the bestowing of animation within the classroom. Excellent and wise choice to sit in his room and absorb his lectures. Not really! This guy is a lunatic!
It has been a while but I recall very good lectures; very learned professor. I recommend taking his classes, if possible

Prof. Petig is one of Stanford's gems! He's truly one of the best professor's I've ever had. He is extremely smart and caring - which makes for a great combination for a student to learn languages. He is one of my favorite professors and I learned more than German with shin, I've learned things that have been important for life. Bravo Herr Petig!
Petig is one of the finest teachers I've ever had.  He keeps class extremely entertaining, but keeps you on your toes and makes you work hard.  Very clear explanations.
Petig is the most helpful and understanding professor I have ever met. Not only is he a great teacher, but he also has a great sense of humor.

Amazing teacher, funny and entertaining but also the best teacher in the German Department. You will learn your stuff without even noticing it. Not hard or strict but you still learn and have fun. Its never hard going to class, there is never a dull moment. Very good at explaining. Best Professor at Stanford.

One of my favorite profs!!!  Insanely funny, and always very helpful.  Willing to meet, plans out of class events for fun, and  always has hilarious stories and sayings.  If you see the name Petig, take the class.  Grading is very fair, not easy, but def. not hard.  If you give effort, you'll earn your A.
Continuing studies course (not sure it is actually '01'): very friendly and approachable, planned gatherings outside of the class too, really liked it.
Nice guy , uses AT THE END OF THE DAY alot ; you can have fun too

Heavy accent, yet writing is very clear, notes are extremely useful.

He is gorgeous. Don't believe me, check out his personal website (linked to the math department's). His lectures were utterly incomprehensable during class, but if I wrote down everything he said, they were very helpful when I read them over (after reading the book). His accent was also very difficult to understand.

Hard class. All the Math 50 series profs are hard but Math 52 is especially hard. They seem to be geniuses who don't understand that we're newbies trying to learn what they've already understood a million times over.

His lectures are difficult; they are all long proofs and he starts 5 minutes before class! He is however, clear if you read ahead of time. He can be (very) condescending but is helpful in office hours. Despite his harsh standards, Fetecau is personable and kind - not to mention brilliant.
Du Bois is the best.
Awesome guy
he is obviously very smart but that does not make him the best teacher. he is way too fast. even the hwk is difficult without TA help. not that clear.

dubois is a good teacher, but he moves way too fast in this class; he skips over a lot. Problem sets are hard; you will learn a lot, but it will be a lot of work!!
The best orgo chem professor I've had at Stanford!

He's incredible. He has this gift for making these pithy comments that get at the heart of things and really help you out. If you can take a seminar with him, DO IT.
Sheehan is nothing short of incredible - thoughtful, incisive, and attentive to student interests.  Take his seminars if you can get in!

This guy goes though an entire lecture as though it's a rehearsed speech - amazing.
One of the best courses I have attended during this Fall
hands on experience, energetic, real life examples, my favorite professor, inspiring

He is my hero. He is the one of the best professors in the world.
Energetic, inspiring, talkative, Digresses with stories.

prof wolff was so nice he is the kindest professor I've had so far and he additionally teaches and displays the English curriculum very well and is understandable. would definitely take again.
Relatable. Awesome. Take this course!
Great Author. I loved his class.

they made a movie about this guy on lifetime and he has a definition on wikipedia.. take him

He showed me that it doesn't take much to connect with another human being.  I have since graduated and teach English at another college.  He is my role model. I will always remember his kindness to me during that time.

Prof. Alexander was one of my best professors in law school.  It's been many years since I was a 1L in her intro Civ Pro class but to this day, I remember her lectures, and even a particular  final exam question on Rule 19, that has been important to me years later i in practice. comment: Take her if you want to learn absolute nothing and be ready to fail.

Had three courses from her when I was a student.  One of my favorites at law school because of her dedication and sincerity.  Actually made Civ Pro come to life for me. Fed Cts was during a difficult period for her so not as good as it could be.  A real gem for SLS!
it's not nearly as complicated as she makes it, and much more interesting than her class suggests

Best professor I've ever had. Great insights into the material. Really enjoys talking to students outside of class. Definitely one of the law school's greatest assets.

Absolutely the worst professor I have ever had in my college career. Rude to students, offended by multi-tasking, which was difficult because listening to him was a waste of time anyway since he never spoke a coherent since during the entire course. Created stupid busy work and had a condescending attitude, on top of all of other short comings.

Prof. Felstiner's teaching was frustrating and incompetent.  While he was amusing to listen to, the effort was almost too much.  He had no logical order in his lectures, and what he taught was pointless and erratic.  And yes, he shrieked in class.  Like a banshee.  (The rest of the course, Lit into Life, was quite enjoyable, however.)

This guy's lectures seem like they're on the verge of being brilliant, but never really quite make it.  You feel like he could be the most interesting person in the world if he only wanted to be.  Sings badly and often.  Has focus issues.  The material of the class holds its own, though, despite the strange lectures.
Prof. Felstiner made me laugh every single lecture.  He always had really interesting things to say and he made lecture highly entertaining!

One of Stanford's finest educators and university leaders.  The man is a legend in his own time.
Very engaging, cares about students.
He's an amazingly committed teacher.

I took this class from him back in 1996 and thought he was one of the best professors in the Engineering program. He uses a lot of experiments, is witty, very clear, and also very fair and nice to his students. Overall a fantastic professor.

I really enjoyed Professor Leben's classes -- so much so that I asked him to be my advisor after I was inspired by him to major in linguistics.  Yes, he is hard of hearing, but when you realize how patient he is with his students, you learn also to be patient with him.
I took this class in the early 90s and his hearing was already shot - I cannot believe that he could still be teaching! A really nice guy, but he's gotta let it go.

An emeritus professor who should officially retire from teaching.

Priya Satia is not a great teacher. She is average. There are much better teachers in the department; unfortunately, she is the one teaching such a pivotal part of history. Also, her first assignment is pretty unclear. She doesn't teach you how to think about history; feels like a high school history class.

I took a graduate-level class with her and three other students. She's good at shepherding discussion along. I don't know that she always added too much to the discussion, but that was cool because it made us talk to each other instead of to her. She could have been a little clearer about assignments though.

excellent course overall. the lectures were very clear and did a good job of unifying the (substantial) course readings. learnt a lot in the course, changed my view of the relationship between britain and its colonies. definitely recommended for anyone with an interest in britain or colonial history.
A most horrible course. I can't believe this counts for higher education.
He is brilliant!!!! Amazing  person and professor. I learned a lot from his class and he was always very very helpful. I hope I can meet with him again in the future. Advice: meet him!
He is a great professor. One of the best! I learned a lot from his class, and I wish I can take the class again in the future with him. He is brilliant and taught me a lot!!
Herndon is brilliant and cares deeply about his students' success. He is what all teachers should be--engaged, kind, and wonderfully intelligent.

He's one of the most gifted teachers and instructors around. If you want to be better @ crafting the English language, you need, NEED!!! to take a class with Scott or meet with him in the writing center...your essays will never be the same after just one session with him...
Great professor! I had a lot of fun in this class. He keeps the class very interesting and it is not outrageously hard.
I thought this was an easy "A", boy was I wrong. He kicked everyone's butt and was very good. He could be more detailed but I guess if he did it would be a long class.
Doc O. was awasome. He was very harsh sometimes but he did the job. I was not sure about him because he was so young but he lived up to the expectations.
He is great. I have never had so much fun learning music history. I didn't I would like it and it was a blast. He was strict but he earned everyone's respect.

I just successfully negotiated an offer for the position I'll be taking out of business school. I couldn't have done it without Professor Karsh's class, and doubt that I would have even tried. She invests a ton of effort in building each student's confidence and skills and models how to be assertive without being a jerk. It's a must-take class.
Great professor with interesting discussions.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Inspirational

comment: I can't say enough positive things about Professor Karsh. She is very generous with her time and feedback. It is obvious that she genuinely cares about each student in the class and believes that the subject matter can help us professionally and personally. Her class was the most practical and useful I took in law school.
She is very experienced, receptive to feedback, and caring towards students. It was a pleasure taking her class.
Most useful class I took in law school. Lessons for life- professional and personal.

admittedly, Fayer doesn't outwardly seem to care much about students in class, but it's mostly just that his enthusiasm for the material comes across more harshly and aggressively than I think he intends. Go to see him in his office for help on hw and final and you will do well AND learn a lot.

Seems like a nice guy but his teaching style was not for me. Totally hands off, no examples, does not really allow students to ask questions. It's all about his powerpoint. If you dont get it, too bad.

Decent lecturer, but discourages asking questions and isn't not very open to interacting with students

I loved this class! Going into it I was skeptical, but I had heard good things about David Como, so I gave it a shot. It ended up being my favorite class of the quarter! His lectures were great and very clear, and the tests were straightforward if you go to lecture and listen. Office hours were helpful, too. I'd love to take another class with him!
Awesome teacher. Very clear, good and engaging lecturer. Class on the Stuarts was very interesting!

the class i took was on the tudors and it was awesome. prof como is interesting and really helpful - plus the tudors are just great. the midterm was pretty easy but the final was kinda hard. but anyway prof como taught me a lot and i had fun.

I've taken a couple classes with him. The colloquium I took was really interesting and I got a lot out of it. He's a little bit boring in lecture, but he really knows his stuff and the material's cool. And he's a total sweetheart.

History 233F - Political Thought in Early Modern Britain - was an expertly-facilitated 3-student colloquium in which we read the great works of British political philosophy, including the Leviathan, and the 2nd Treatise of Government.  Dr. Como treated the course as a discussion group supplemented with brief lectures.  I learned a great deal.
best prof
Simply one of the best Economics professors at Stanford, and he's not even tenured. I hate stats, but this man is so pedagogical, he made the lectures super engaging. GOATED.
Most talented lecturer at Stanford by far.
Fantastic lecturer. Best professor I've had so far at Stanford. Class is hard but fair, and he works hard to set you up for success.

Prof. McKeon has a stellar reputation and it's easy to see why. Crisp, clear and funny lectures with Feynman-esque explanations for difficult concepts. His classes keep you on your toes though, so come ready with determination and don't procrastinate on his difficult psets.
rating_tags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Amazing lectures

comment: Does not honor accommodations and there is so much unnecessary work.
The best PWR teacher. period.
Just terrific, a role model for all of us

Donna is enthusiastic and knowledgeable. She engages the class in the already-interesting discussion of the meaning of criminality. Her extension policy is great; she cares more about your learning than school policy.
Always gives extensions, no matter what!
Really interesting class. Winstein really cares about helping you learn, and as long as you engage with lectures and go to lab sessions, you'll do fine in the class.
Disorganized and unable to convey the primary learning goals of his class.
GODSEND. One of the best instructors @ Stanford

Friendly and enthusiastic, but very confusing in lecture - I understood some material prior to lecture and left confused. I took to reading my textbook in class instead of listening, which served me surprisingly well.
He is good and clear but not nearly as interesting as Boxer. He can make you learn but he can't make you care.

Great lecturer (much better than Boxer). Provides great in-class examples that he works out step by step. If you can understand his examples and work out the book problems on your own the tests won't be a problem. I agree that each question counts for too much of the grade on midterms.
Waymouth is a very clear and organized lecturer. He is also very helpful in office hours. Too much weight is put on each question on the tests in this class though.

This class is most defintely NOT a repeat of AP Chemistry.  Boxer and Waymouth go out of their way to make the testing material above and beyond rote calculation.  Don't expect to see problems of the test's difficulty at any time before examination day.

Nice, but stressed teacher. The class is OK, lots of busy work and group work, but not that challenging, my high school writing teacher taught me more about how to write well and gave me a lot more helpful comments.
Super nice, a little confusing, interesting ideas, boring exercises, but I hear most PWR classes have a lot of busywork too, basically EASY

Clear expectations, friendly, professional. Goes out of her way to make class interesting and engaging, and to remind students when stuff is due. Gives access to plenty of resources. Always seeks feedback on teaching. Brings in breakfast for everyone sometimes.

Teacher was confusing, unhelpful, unfriendly and not nice. She is a rigid grader yet it is extremely confusing to figure out what she wants so you can not discern what guidelines she is actually imposing and what she really wants! I wish I had saved myself the time, money and aggravation and not taken this course!
Shes not a very good teacher at all. Very difficult to comprehend her lectures.
Cute
Smokin hot

I found much of this class a waste of my time.  We are asked to read about a dozen different theories of adolescent development and force fit them to a case study student. Great role model
I just want to say TAKE THIS TEACHER to get an A.
She is good. Clear communicator and very caring. Makes you learn.

Professor Walters is a compassionate professor. I have not seen many professors who care about their students success as she does. Dr. Walters did a fine job of making an otherwise uninteresting topic (to an engineer) interesting. She genuinely cared about her student's success. Her lectures were well organized and she seemed very well informed of the lecture topics. She has a great sense of humor and is a fair professor.

Overall a very poor professor. Lectures were disorganized, and it was clear that Prof Walters was not prepared for them. She often spoke with a condescending tone.

fun teacher, generally pretty easy

nice guy. confusing rambles.

comment: Henry comes down to UCSC once a year to teach the History of Digital Games course . The course is really interesting but can have its few dry moments. There are 2 projects which are really easy, 2 random in class quizzes so go to class, and a final in essay format for which he releases the 5 prompts early, he picks 3 and from there we pick 2.
rating_tags: Get ready to read--Amazing lectures--Would take again

comment: Meh. Wasn't my cup of tea. He had pretty interesting content though, so if you like digital archiving, then consider it. But he was a little confusing and unclear on his expectations of the class.

Do you like condescending instructors? Instructors who think their class is the only one you are taking? Lots of reading that has nothing to do with assignments? Understands that his time is precious, but your time means nothing? The feeling that you've read a lot/done lots of work but learned very little? Then this guy is for you!
rating_tags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: I took his History of games and he was very enthusiastic and happy to share all his knowledge, by far the best professor iv'e had as of yet, If I can take more classes with him i'll do it in a heartbeat.

What a joke. His teaching is so bad that maybe 20% of the class attended lecture after the first week. Lectures were dry and the exams looked nothing like we were taught. The class averages were also dismal, but atleast he made the curve high to offset his garbage teaching skills.

After 2 weeks I realised that Gratta's voice was going to kill me and I would rather just read the textbook or talk to TAs. He doesn't make it clear when things are important and therefore makes it impossible to take useful notes. Thankfully most people taking this class are doing it for a requirement so it was easy to stay above the curve.

Unclear everything - subject materials, tests, and grading. I got a B+ with no real explanation, even when I scored well above the median on tests. Did not learn a thing from his lectures. So, so terrible.
Terrible, so terrible.
Just okay - not great, not bad either.  Made physics 45 pretty easy.
He really knows his stuff
Excellent instructor.  His game theory course was terrific; I have heard his ethnic conflicts course is also very good.
this guy sucks
No Comments

One of the best professors at SLS; only caveat is an occasional tendency to ramble and then have to rush through material to make up for it, but the rambling is almost always entertaining and informative in it's own right. Extraordinarily approachable both in and out of class- a must-take for anyone interested in criminal law.

Look up mensch in the OyED to find his picture.  Old School in the sense that his progressive politics masks a reactionary streak.  But what a great intellect and fine person even if he is caught up in the institutional politics.  Great teacher but sometimes too disparaging of  economics in attempt to uplift law and humanities.
he's great

Great professor.  Funny, really into the material.  And cares about students and teaching a LOT.  Not always the clearest at explaning things, and assigns a lot of reading.  But more than makes up for it with his intelligence, wit, and dedication to teaching.

Interesting class with experienced instructor, he always bring up to date info. to the class with clear instructions . If you want to learn about Crypto and NFTs take his class . I will take his next class about Metaverse .

His Tech 03 Cryptocurrency and NFT class was great , I wish I took it before investing in crypto , he knows this topic very well , he answers questions in class and reply to emails promptly , good class and good instructor .

I am taking his Tech 03 crypto class online after taking CS 03 Blockchain class last quarter, he is the expert in this topic , very attentive to students questions , his lectures are highly interactive with up to date info.,

Prof. Banafa is a great instructor , knows his subject very well , respected in the field of Blockchain . I learned a lot from his class and I recommend it for anyone who wants to understand Blockchain Tech. You need to attend all his lectures to understand the topic .
Great professor, very caring and prioritizes the students
Not nice to students.
Not a good lecturer, and not supportive of students.
Energetic and enthusiastic. She'll make you love the material.

his tests are really hard but if you get butschered and survived his class, you're pretty much sure that you can pass the harder courses ahead of you. not really a bad professor but if you dont have the will to stay in the course and work harder, you'll die.
I *really* learned math with him. His tests are pretty  hard, but if you do all the book questions you should be fine. Very nice guy outside of class.

I thought his class was hard but really good.  His lectures are more theory than practice examples. If you do his problem sets carefully, the tests are not too bad, though they are still hard. He is a really cool guy to talk to, too.
No Comments

I took her online class over the Summer and she wasn't really involved. When i submitted papers and assignments she would take her time in grading them and would give me little to no feedback on them. At the end of he semester she marked everything off with an A and sent me on my way. Not that I'm complaining about that, i just wanted feedback.
rating_tags: Tough Grader--SO MANY PAPERS--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: LOVED her! She is absolutely amazing, the best TA I have had during my four years at Stanford. Extremely clear with her subject matter, all her relations are really insightful. I just cannot say enough good things about her. The only thing I've heard is that she's hard. I did well in her class, but I went to office hours to clarify paper topics.

Our meetings really helped me get started writing papers. After meeting with her I knew what I wanted to say and I was excited to start writing (this NEVER happens to me!). I enjoyed our sections although I didn't enjoy many of the works we studied. She made IHUM a good experience for me, which given IHUM and especially this course is saying a lot.
****, ****, ****.  No help with writing essays, no insight provided other than her own ideas which we cannot use.  Smoking, hateful, etc.
An exceptional professor.
No Comments
No Comments
Best professor I've had at Stanford. Funny, informative, and interesting. I would love to take more of his classes, even though I'm not into business and public policy, which are his main fields.

Dylan is the kinda guy that makes you excited to come to class every day. His excitement, kindness, and passion make his class fun and interesting. He reminded me why I got into CS in the first place and I can't wait to take more classes with him in the future.

I'm not a Stanford student so I can't compare this to previous iterations. However, I felt like Dylan was an excellent teacher and turned discrete math into a topic that was very engaging. We had great conversations and he even emailed me once to see if I was doing okay. So he's a genuine, great guy. Also very funny.
CS103 instructor. Great class. Problem sets were actually really interesting towards the end of the course.
He is nice, but the course CS 103 is SO DIFFICULT!!!
A very talented and inspiring professor. One of my favorites at SLS.

Wow!  An outlook and approach that synthesizes east coast intensity with west coast cool.  One of my favorites in law school and an inspiration for my career.  Made class a pleasure and made the profession of being law professor look like the challenge and joy that it is.
one of the most clear, organized lecturers at SLS.  very engaging and makes the material interesting.
rock on

Lazy. Basically turns the class over to students to teach and uses student final papers to supplement her casebook. The cliche of a liberal who means well, but is hopelessly stuck in her white, middle-class world view. Also, thinks very highly of herself.
Boring, and quite enamored with her own accomplishments (she loves to cite herself).
brrr...
She is awful

Good teacher, even though initially he honestly expected at least half of us to fail/drop his course (and would remind us how hard his class was). That said, he was a great lecturer and I learned a ton from his class.
He assigned problem sets from the book but tested exclusively on completely different material, namely, his handouts on field theory. Not a good job at all.

Professor Brumfiel is, for lack of a better word, blustering.  His lectures for Math110 were mediocre, but for a grad level class I bet he'd be a lot better.  He's really great during office hours, though.
No Comments

Adam's a fantastic section leader--some of the best discussions I've had here at Stanford were in section for this class. Plus, he's super eloquent, knows his stuff, and kicks ass in a suit (just sayin', doesn't hurt). I will say that he can come off as cold and intimidating at first, but he actually cares and is really willing to help you.
Adam was the best teacher much less section leader I have had at Stanford.  He's hard, but you will come out so much the better for it.
Really enjoyed the class, always stay after class because he gives you a lot of feedback if you ask.
umm... really cares about teaching, goes out of his way to help his students, and brings his dog to class.

John Pauly presents very complicated and useful material in a clear and concise way.  His caring shows in every aspect of his teaching.  And his expertise is unmatched.  It was a privilege to take this class from him.
No Comments
Best Class I've ever taken from the best prof.
Prof Pauly basically straight from the lecture notes. He tends to be a soft spoken lecturer so it can lull people to sleep. Nice guy overall though.

When discussing Satz's theory of "Noxious Markets," the professor chose as an example "a market no one could find noxious, like bananas." When a student reminded him about Guatemala and United Fruit he changed the subject. That same class, he made a joke about Banana Republic being his favorite store. No irony, no awareness of history, just myopia.

It's an ethics class and there is no discussion of core philosophers on the subject, such as Nietzsche and Foucault, instead focusing on sophomoric utilitarians like Nozick and Rawls. Validates dominant cultures while ignoring any theories by people of color. Laden in normative theory with neither space for emancipatory thought nor postmodernism.
Professor Rozeboom is awesome! His class challenged me to think harder than I ever had. Show up, do the work, and don't forget to participate!

Professor Rozeboom has been my favorite teacher in college. Work hard and get an A. I didn't care about ethics before this class but I truly enjoyed each and every class. HIs clarity is amazing and he may be the definition of a genius. Truly a pleasure being in his class.
Good course.

He has a preoccupation with notation that I felt was not necessary for this level of course (save it for 341!). His lecture notes were inconsistent at times with his board writing, and there was no text to reinforce the concepts, which were explained poorly in class. I will avoid Weber for any future classes unless they're required for my degree.
This was a cool course. Lots of practical applications! I would recommend this if you are willing to put in some time. Prof has funny stories. Drawback: course only offered for 3 units.
One of the worst professors I've had. His final was so hard and poorly written, that he said "If you understood it completely, you should be teaching the class"
A horribly unclear lecturer who plainly needs to get over her own ego.
Professor Rice is wonderful. Obviously she's very knowledgable, but she is an amazing teacher as well. She challenges you, but is very willing to help.
Amazing professor.
I Love this professor.  I think she could run for president if she wanted to.
Good professor
Very great professor
very inspiring professor! You can feel in every class that he loves his field and enjoys sharing his passion for mathematics with his students.
No Comments

Kahn is one of the best professors I had at Stanford. I took his course, EE102A, the first year he designed it. He has a deep expertise and love for the material, he's hilarious (often unintentionally and in a meme-y way), and he is passionate about helping you learn. I struggled but he inspired and helped me in OH until I was able to get an A!
There should be memes of Professor Kahn. HE IS SO FUNNY!
He puts you to sleep. Shouldn't be teaching. One of the worst professors at Stanford.
Just terrible.  Lecture notes are bad.  What's worse is that he refuses to post them online. Monotone voice.  List goes on.

Professor McKibben is extremely thoughtful, knowledgeable, and kind. She took the time to work with every student to help them develop a research topic and made herself available throughout the quarter when students had questions. I liked that while she gave input, she still let students pick which roads to go down, meaning the did not micromanage.

Professor Mckibben is passionate professor with a student centered approach. Her assigned materials were interesting and useful if your researching or curious about California and the West. While in class discussions diverged at times, the overall course was interesting, I got feedback on readings related to my own work, which also was a plus.
She's disorganized and can be pompous and overly judgmental.
A great and interesting class, but it was very unorganized. Papers were fairly graded, and the final was a couple of short, take-home essay questions.
Amazing person!
One of the best professors and physicists in the world now.
Very relatable. Makes Quantum Physics accessible to the common person
Amazing
terrible
Lei Xing is too old. When he was younger he used to be better but these days he is slow.
Good thing he doesnt teach that much.
Not very clear. Very indirect.

Bert is incredibly knowledgeable on a wide range of subjects. I still meet with Bert occasionally and ask him for advice (about academics as well as life in general). And even though I'm now pursuing degrees in economics and statistics, Bert is still more helpful than any academic advisor. I recommend taking as many classes as you can with him.
He's a great teacher and very interesting. He genuinely cares about his students, and really, when you're a student, you cannot ask for anything more.

Bert is an incredible person.  He genuinely cares about his students and he will go above and beyond to make sure you are learning.  He has a tendency to digress, but his digressions are always super interesting so it's worth it and he always makes sure you learn what you you need to know.
Very nice guy. Weird and off topic at times but he is a good teacher and you learn the latin he teaches...
AWESOME.
curmudgeonly-hot.  it's unnerving how charismatic he is.

He told me that the coloring puzzles at Denny's held the key to eternal happiness. All you have to do is hold them upside down. Mind boggling!!

You will learn a lot from Rush Rehm. He has radical ideas and discussions are always heated, interesting, and enlightening. Although he assigns a large workload and grades hard, I learned more in his class than in all my other classes combined that quarter. Therefore, I will never regret my decision to take the class.

Rush is a very interesting prof, and he taught an interesting class.  He is very helpful and a nice guy.  But there is an extreme amount of work (a book assigned per class) and he grades hard.  People say that fuzzies have it easier and have less work that techies, but Rush tries to make that not true.
Awesome.  Rush is brilliant.  Any chance you get, take his class.
Awesome class - Rehm knows a lot about liberal interpretations of the media, gov't etc. - highly recommended

He is the best professor I ever got. I took his Engr 30 Thermodynamics. He gave amazing lectures with vivid examples. To show us the working mechanism of a fridge, he actually brought one into the classroom and broke it. His homework is a little bit hard, but if you pay attention, you will be fine. The textbook is very helpful.
Chris is awesome.

Chris is one of my favorite teachers.  He is highly knowledgeable about energy systems and passionate about what he teaches.  You can tell that he cares about students a lot and I really appreciated his willingness to talk with students and answer questions.

Very arrogant. Loved to make things more complicated than they needed to be. Thought the whole Mecahnical Engineering curriculum should be centered around thermodynamics. I have been working in industry for several years and that is the subject area that I use least from the core courses.
Sheri is not only an incredibly dedicated teacher, she is also a wonderful person.
She teaches with enthusiasm and tries very hard to get the concepts across to the students
No Comments

Fascinating old-timey classics professor.   Tweedy and loves to tell stories.   Brilliant but still approachable and kind.   Loved him.
He's insane, but entertaining.

He is nice and helpful.
Practical, passionate, probably the best in my 4 years of undergrad.
Best prof ever. He's an amazing teacher and an even better academic advisor. ;-) If you think you might be an AA major/minor definitely ask him to advise you.

Springer is really great - he's interesting, and he explains things in an easy-to-understand fashion, even if you don't know much about the subject at all.  He has great anecdotes (he's an expert in his field) and hands-on activities, and he cares about his students.  Take this class!
This guy is awesome!!  he knows his stuff, has very helpful photos of everything imaginable.  He also has one heck of a story to tell and is a comedian to boot.
The course is hard, and his exams are harder. But it's still great to take it with him because he's such a master at this, and is available if you need any help. I learned a lot with this course.

I took him years ago. He was very kind and helpful and always tried to answer everyone's questions. His lectures tended to emphasize details; you had to construct the big picture on your own. Could have been more clear, but a good prof and a good guy.
He tells students that homework scores are not taken into account for the final grade, but...... His surly attitude takes away joy from the learning process.

Prof. Siegmund is very patient, teaches at a decent pace, and is very willing to be interrupted and asked questions.  Stats116 is still hard, but Prof. Siegmund may be a good professor to take it with.
she's too outdated and isn't open to hearing new ideas even when backed by multiple students and text

Kind of outdated in perspectives and teachings -- you can provide evidence for some things that you interpret from the reading and it doesnt feel welcome. She also forgets things easily which makes it tough to streamline conversations
She's a really nice person and she encourages people to share their ideas, even if she doesn't agree with them.

comment: A lovely person; she gives you a lot of space to express and discuss your own ideas

comment: Awesome professor. She cares about student's opinions and makes the class into an open conversation rather than a strict lecture which encourages intellectual growth. Definitely reccomend taking one of her courses.

comment: Prof. Vermeule  is a space cadet. When she isn't looking at her reflection, she is very self-absorbed and at times less than lucid. Overall, an easy class. I'm not certain this class topic was the best fit for her.

My experience with this professor was awful. He was very unhelpful and I ended up learning everything on my own without his help. I should have just stared at the wall rather than wasted my time in this class. He did not BUMP my grade up!

super SMART

Khalil is a tough but fair man who is dedicated to teaching his students not only language but culture.  I rank him among the most valuable professors I have ever studied from.  Arabic is a hard language - and Khalil's classes are not easy - but they are eminently rewarding and worthwhile.

Khalil is an animated, concerned teacher that is always willing to answer questions. He clearly has his students in mind, and definitely has made something as seemingly incomprehensible as Arabic into a manageable class. He is particularly good at getting us to learn outside of the book.

Khalil is fun, animated, and demonstrates a genuine concern over whether his students are learning.  He is very approachable and, while the class moves quite fast, a little effort can make it tremendously valuable.  He is a linguistic genius, but is incredibly humble about it.  I would highly recommend any of his classes.

One of the best classes I've ever taken. He is by far the most intelligent person I've ever heard, and he doesn't really try to come down to the typical student's level. Must have a strong background in the liberal arts (LOT of continental philosophy) to understand his lectures, which seem to be pretty extemporaneous but are extremely interesting.

This guy is a really famous composer (reportedly the highest paid composer in academia).  I was really excited to have a seminar with him but unfortunately he couldn't care less about this class.  No assigned pieces to look at before class, basically no syllabus.  Don't waste your time with the class, just go read his books.
He is a terrible lecturer.  His compositions may be famous, but that sure doesn't mean he can teach.
I really recommend this class. Its so great! Professor Kargin is an amazing teacher and has so much to share! Best class at Stanford
This is a great professor. Although he is hard to understand, he really cares about his students and does everything to help them. Take this class its really awesome!!!
Professor Kargin is almost impossible to understand. The class is terrible. I haven't learned a thing from lecture, just from the book and section.
Great teacher! 5/5 would advise a friend.

comment: Worst class I've taken in the History Department. Lectures are unclear, rambling, and frustratingly pointless. Do yourself a favor and avoid her at all costs. There are too many great courses at Stanford to waste any time in her classes.
Fantastic professor, encyclopedic knowledge, brilliant, helpful, and enthusiastic. Pretty sure her mind works twice as quickly as your average mortal, but that's why she's a Stanford professor.

He was my favorite professor from college. I graduated in 2013 but found myself on this site and thought I'd rate him (took the history of Darwinism course). Fantastic writer, informative/inspiring speaker, and a humble "non-believer" (as a spiritual person I respected his conviction). Graded harder than I thought but oh well.
Clear and easy to understand.  Engaging for students and very kind to students having a hard time.  Answers questions concisely and completely unless the answer is unknown.  Great lecturer

Immediately recognized him from his videos. LOVE HIM!!
Great dude! Really passionate about what he teaches.

Nancy Zhang is really nice, and she's quite an amusing character, but she's a horrible professor... take it with someone else if you can.

Great teacher
Great in every way. Excited about the material. Excited about teaching. Loves to chat with students. Super supportive and devoted to producing people who think seriously about CS and do good work

It's hard to say this without sounding ridiculous, but he is honestly the best professor I have ever had.
